# Stroke Risk Prediction Using Machine Learning and SHAP Interpretability

## Overview

Stroke is one of the leading causes of death and long-term disability worldwide. Early identification of individuals at high risk can significantly improve prevention and treatment outcomes.

This project develops a machine learning pipeline that predicts stroke risk using patient health data. The workflow includes data preprocessing, handling class imbalance, training several machine learning models, evaluating their performance, and preparing the model for interpretability using SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations).

The primary goal of this project is not only to build a predictive model but also to understand which health factors contribute most strongly to stroke risk.

---

## Dataset

The dataset used in this project is the Healthcare Stroke Dataset. It contains demographic and medical information about patients that can be used to predict whether a stroke has occurred.

Important features in the dataset include:

Gender – The gender of the patient
Age – The patient's age
Hypertension – Whether the patient has hypertension
Heart Disease – Whether the patient has heart disease
Ever Married – Marital status
Work Type – Type of employment
Residence Type – Whether the patient lives in an urban or rural area
Average Glucose Level – Average blood glucose level in the blood
BMI – Body Mass Index
Smoking Status – Smoking history
Stroke – Target variable indicating whether the patient experienced a stroke

One major challenge of the dataset is that it is highly imbalanced. Only about five percent of the patients experienced a stroke, while the majority did not. Because of this imbalance, special techniques must be used to ensure the model properly learns patterns related to stroke risk.

---

## Project Workflow

The project follows a complete machine learning workflow from raw data to model evaluation.

The major steps include:

1. Data Loading
2. Exploratory Data Analysis
3. Data Cleaning
4. Feature Engineering
5. Data Visualization
6. Train/Test Splitting
7. Feature Scaling
8. Handling Class Imbalance
9. Model Training
10. Model Evaluation
11. Threshold Optimization
12. Precision-Recall Analysis

---

## Data Loading

The dataset is loaded using the Python library Pandas. After loading the dataset, the ID column is removed because it does not contain predictive information.

Removing non-informative columns prevents unnecessary noise in the model.

---

## Exploratory Data Analysis

Exploratory data analysis is performed to better understand the dataset.

During this phase, the following analyses are conducted:

Inspection of data types
Checking for missing values
Summary statistics for each variable
Distribution analysis of important variables

This step helps identify issues in the data such as missing values or unexpected distributions.

---

## Data Cleaning

The dataset contains missing values in the BMI column. Instead of removing those rows, the missing BMI values are replaced using the median BMI of the dataset.

Median imputation is chosen because it is less sensitive to outliers than the mean.

Cleaning the dataset ensures that machine learning algorithms can properly process the data.

---

## Feature Engineering

Machine learning models require numerical inputs, so categorical variables must be transformed.

Several encoding methods are used:

Binary Encoding
Binary categorical variables such as gender, marital status, and residence type are converted into numerical values.

Handling Rare Categories
The dataset contains a very small number of entries labeled as "Other" in the gender column. Because this category appears extremely rarely, it is replaced with the more common category to avoid instability during training.

One-Hot Encoding
Categorical variables with multiple categories, such as work type and smoking status, are converted using one-hot encoding. This creates separate columns for each category while avoiding the dummy variable trap by dropping one redundant category.

---

## Data Visualization

Visualization techniques are used to understand patterns within the data.

Important visualizations include:

Stroke distribution plot
Age distribution grouped by stroke occurrence
Correlation heatmap between variables

These visualizations reveal several insights:

Stroke risk increases significantly with age
Hypertension and heart disease are correlated with stroke risk
Higher glucose levels appear associated with stroke probability

Understanding these relationships helps guide model development.

---

## Train/Test Split

The dataset is split into training and testing sets.

The training set is used to train machine learning models, while the testing set is used to evaluate how well the model performs on unseen data.

Stratified sampling is used so that both the training and testing sets maintain the same stroke-to-non-stroke ratio as the original dataset.

---

## Feature Scaling

Several machine learning algorithms perform better when numerical features are scaled.

Standardization is applied to numerical features so that they have a mean of zero and a standard deviation of one.

This ensures that variables with larger scales do not dominate the learning process.

---

## Handling Class Imbalance

Because stroke cases are rare in the dataset, the model may otherwise learn to simply predict "no stroke" for most patients.

To address this problem, SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique) is used.

SMOTE generates synthetic examples of the minority class, allowing the model to better learn patterns associated with stroke cases.

This significantly improves the model’s ability to detect strokes.

---

## Machine Learning Models

Several models are trained and compared in this project.

Logistic Regression
Logistic regression is used as a baseline model. It is simple, interpretable, and commonly used in medical prediction tasks.

Decision Tree
Decision trees create rule-based models that split data based on feature values. They can capture nonlinear relationships between variables.

Random Forest
Random forest is an ensemble learning method that combines multiple decision trees. It reduces overfitting and usually provides stronger predictive performance.

---

## Class Weight Adjustment

To further address the imbalance in stroke cases, models are trained with balanced class weights.

This increases the penalty for misclassifying stroke cases, forcing the model to pay greater attention to the minority class.

---

## Threshold Optimization

Most classification models use a default probability threshold of 0.5.

However, in medical prediction problems, missing a true stroke case can be extremely dangerous.

For this reason, the classification threshold is lowered. Lower thresholds increase recall, meaning the model catches more potential stroke cases even if it produces more false positives.

In healthcare applications, this trade-off is often preferred.

---

## Model Evaluation

Models are evaluated using several performance metrics.

Confusion Matrix
The confusion matrix shows the number of true positives, true negatives, false positives, and false negatives.

Precision
Precision measures how many predicted stroke cases were actually strokes.

Recall
Recall measures how many real stroke cases the model successfully detected.

F1 Score
The F1 score balances precision and recall.

Because the dataset is imbalanced, recall is particularly important.

---

## Precision-Recall Analysis

Precision-recall curves are used to evaluate model performance.

Unlike accuracy, precision-recall analysis is better suited for imbalanced datasets because it focuses specifically on how well the model identifies the minority class.

Models are compared based on their precision-recall curves and average precision scores.

---

## Future Work

Several improvements are planned for future versions of the project.

SHAP Interpretability
SHAP will be used to interpret the predictions made by the model. This will help determine which features most strongly influence stroke risk and provide explanations for individual predictions.

Advanced Models
Future experiments may include gradient boosting models such as XGBoost or LightGBM.

Hyperparameter Tuning
Grid search or randomized search can be used to optimize model parameters.

Cross Validation
Cross validation will improve the reliability of performance estimates.

